DISTRIBUTED WEB INFRASTRUCTURE
================================

INFRASTRUCTURE OVERVIEW:
User → HAProxy Load Balancer → Server 1 (Nginx + App + MySQL Primary)
                             → Server 2 (Nginx + App + MySQL Replica)

ADDITIONAL ELEMENTS AND WHY:
-----------------------------
1. LOAD BALANCER (HAProxy): Distributes incoming traffic between 2 servers
   to avoid overloading a single server and improve availability.

2. SERVER 2: Second server added for redundancy and to handle more traffic.
   If Server 1 fails, Server 2 continues serving requests.

3. MySQL REPLICA: Added for data redundancy and read performance.

LOAD BALANCER CONFIGURATION:
-----------------------------
Algorithm: Round Robin
How it works: Each request is sent to the next server in sequence.
Server 1 gets request 1, Server 2 gets request 2, Server 1 gets request 3...

Active-Active vs Active-Passive:
- Active-Active: Both servers handle traffic simultaneously (our setup).
- Active-Passive: One server handles traffic, other is on standby.
  Passive server activates only if active server fails.
Our setup uses ACTIVE-ACTIVE.

DATABASE PRIMARY-REPLICA CLUSTER:
----------------------------------
- Primary (Master) node: Handles all WRITE operations (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
  Changes are replicated to Replica node.
- Replica (Slave) node: Receives copies of data from Primary.
  Handles READ operations only.

PRIMARY vs REPLICA for application:
- Application writes data ONLY to Primary node.
- Application can read data from Replica node to reduce Primary load.

ISSUES WITH THIS INFRASTRUCTURE:
---------------------------------
1. SPOF: Load balancer is a single point of failure.
   If HAProxy goes down, entire website becomes unreachable.

2. SECURITY ISSUES:
   - No firewall: Servers are exposed to direct attacks.
   - No HTTPS: Traffic between users and servers is unencrypted.
   - Sensitive data can be intercepted.

3. NO MONITORING: No way to detect server failures, high CPU usage,
   or abnormal traffic patterns in real time.
